WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.540
So when we think about hallucinations, there are two major places
where we can intervene as the human in the loop.

00:00:07.040 --> 00:00:11.240
The first is the input side,
and then the second is the output side.

00:00:11.240 --> 00:00:17.940
We're going to talk through some strategies for evaluating
your outputs for hallucinations, but it starts with your input.

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:24.120
If you are cognizant and thoughtful about the things
that you're asking...

00:00:24.120 --> 00:00:29.060
...the way that you're prompting the large language model,
then you can mitigate the vast majority of hallucinations.

00:00:29.060 --> 00:00:34.440
Some of the strategies and phrases
that you can use to mitigate these are...

00:00:34.740 --> 00:00:38.700
"Provide citations for the claim."
"Can you link me to the original study?"

00:00:38.700 --> 00:00:42.700
"List three reputable sources
that support this statement..."

00:00:42.700 --> 00:00:48.960
"...and then quote the specific sentence from your source
that contains this information."

00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:54.440
All of these are strategies that we're going to use
in different ways going forward.

00:00:54.440 --> 00:00:59.040
But if you build them in from the beginning and force
the language model to not just say, "Yeah, Shakespeare said this"...

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:04.020
...but also to say, "Where did he say it?
What was the context?"

00:01:04.020 --> 00:01:09.280
"Can you give me other sources for what
William Shakespeare said about video games?"

00:01:09.280 --> 00:01:11.340
Then eventually it's going to say,
"Oh, he didn't actually say anything." It admits the truth.
